---
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
---
<BaseLayout
  title="SkanPay - QR Payment Gateway for In-Store Transactions"
  description="SkanPay helps merchants and payment partners support QR code payment experiences for in-store and mobile wallet transactions."
  activePath="/"
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">QR payment gateway</p>
      <h1>QR payment infrastructure for in-store acceptance</h1>
      <p class="hero-copy">
        SkanPay supports structured QR payment conversations for merchants, payment apps, mobile wallets, and loyalty platforms entering physical-store checkout.
      </p>
      <div class="button-row">
        <a class="button primary" href="/contact/">Contact SkanPay</a>
        <a class="button secondary" href="/qr-payments/">Explore QR Payments</a>
      </div>
      <div class="trust-strip" aria-label="SkanPay focus areas">
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>01</strong>
          Merchant checkout
        </div>
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>02</strong>
          Wallet-ready QR flow
        </div>
        <div class="trust-item">
          <strong>03</strong>
          Partner integration support
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <aside class="hero-panel" aria-label="SkanPay platform overview">
      <div class="panel-header">
        <span>Platform overview</span>
        <strong>SkanPay</strong>
      </div>
      <div class="system-card">
        <div>
          <span>Acceptance channel</span>
          <strong>In-store QR code payment</strong>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Primary participants</span>
          <strong>Merchant, customer, payment app</strong>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Transaction states</span>
          <strong>Created, scanned, authorized, confirmed</strong>
        </div>
        <div>
          <span>Commercial focus</span>
          <strong>Merchant onboarding and partner enablement</strong>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="signal-grid">
        <div><span>Flow</span><strong>QR request</strong></div>
        <div><span>Status</span><strong>Readable</strong></div>
        <div><span>Audience</span><strong>B2B</strong></div>
        <div><span>Scope</span><strong>Gateway</strong></div>
      </div>
    </aside>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Transaction model</p>
        <h2>Define the transaction before integration begins</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        QR payment projects need clear state definitions, merchant expectations, customer actions, and partner responsibilities.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="flow-table" aria-label="QR payment transaction model">
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>1. Present</strong>
        <p>Merchant creates or displays a checkout-specific QR code.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>2. Scan</strong>
        <p>Customer opens the payment request in a supported wallet or app.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>3. Authorize</strong>
        <p>Customer reviews the amount and approves or cancels the payment.</p>
      </article>
      <article>
        <span>Step</span>
        <strong>4. Confirm</strong>
        <p>Merchant receives a clear status before closing the checkout.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section technical-band">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Where SkanPay fits</p>
      <h2>A practical layer between checkout and mobile payment experiences</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        SkanPay positions QR payment as an operational workflow, not just a code on the counter. The focus is the handoff between merchant checkout, customer approval, and partner payment experiences.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Merchant</span>
        <h3>Checkout state</h3>
        <p>Clear payment status language for staff at the counter.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Customer</span>
        <h3>Scan and approve</h3>
        <p>A familiar mobile action connected to a visible request.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card data-card">
        <span>Partner</span>
        <h3>Integration boundary</h3>
        <p>Defined responsibilities for wallet, loyalty, or payment apps.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section split">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Readiness model</p>
      <h2>What needs to be clear before a launch conversation</h2>
      <p class="section-intro">
        The site now reads more like a serious payment-operations product: clear scope, clear stakeholders, and clear next questions.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="spec-panel">
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>QR session</span>
        <p>Create a payment request customers can open from the checkout counter.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Authorization</span>
        <p>Describe the customer approval state without making unsupported processing claims.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Confirmation</span>
        <p>Make merchant-facing success, failure, and pending states easy to reason about.</p>
      </div>
      <div class="spec-row">
        <span>Support path</span>
        <p>Route real merchant, wallet, and cooperation questions to SkanPay.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Use cases</p>
        <h2>Built for payment conversations with real operators</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        The content is organized around practical business questions instead of feature claims.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>Merchant</span>
        <h3>Add a QR payment option</h3>
        <p>Plan how staff present the request, read the result, and support customers.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>Payment app</span>
        <h3>Enter the checkout moment</h3>
        <p>Connect an existing mobile payment relationship to an in-store action.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card route-card">
        <span>Loyalty</span>
        <h3>Link rewards and payment</h3>
        <p>Explore payment flows that can work alongside offers and customer engagement.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-heading">
      <div>
        <p class="eyebrow">Professional standard</p>
        <h2>Measured language for a serious payments audience</h2>
      </div>
      <p>
        The site avoids invented customer logos, processor promises, and compliance claims until those details are confirmed.
      </p>
    </div>
    <div class="grid three">
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Concrete operating language</h3>
        <p>Visitors see transaction states, participants, and support responsibilities.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Responsible scope</h3>
        <p>Security, reporting, and settlement language stays practical until integrations are confirmed.</p>
      </article>
      <article class="card">
        <h3>Clear inquiry path</h3>
        <p>Prospects can identify the inquiry type and send details to support@skanpay.us.</p>
      </article>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="cta-band">
    <div>
      <p class="eyebrow">Next step</p>
      <h2>Bring QR payment conversations into focus.</h2>
      <p>Share the merchant, partner, or product details you want SkanPay to support and the team can follow up directly.</p>
    </div>
    <a class="button secondary" href="/contact/">Start a Conversation</a>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
